{{other people||William Brooks (disambiguation)}}
{{inline|date=October 2016}}
'''William Brooks''' (1762–1846) was a supplier of cotton to spinners around [[Whalley, Lancashire|Whalley]] and [[Blackburn]].

He was the son of John Brooks of Waddington, Lancashire.

He went into partnership with Roger Cunliffe, of the Cunliffe family of Great Harwood, who had been [[Mercer (occupation)|mercers]] since Elizabethan times. At first cotton manufacturing was the main activity, but in 1792 they founded [[Cunliffe, Brooks|Cunliffe Brooks Bank]] at Blackburn. On Brooks' death in 1846 the bank moved its head office to Manchester.

He had married Sarah Greenall, the daughter of Richard Greenall They had three sons, including John and [[Samuel Brooks (railway pioneer)|Samuel]] and a daughter, Nancy. They lived near [[Whalley, Lancashire]].

